.SS Ignore patterns
The \f[B]ignore.tmpl\f[R] file (rendered as template, then parsed as
glob patterns) controls which files are skipped during apply and status.
Patterns are matched against paths relative to \f[B]files/\f[R].
Supports \f[B]*\f[R], \f[B]?\f[R], \f[B]**\f[R].
.SS Permissions
The \f[B]perms\f[R] file defines permission rules for deployed files:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# pattern              mode   owner  group\f[R]
etc/**/                0755   root   root
etc/**                 0644   root   root
etc/security/          0700   root   root
.EE
.PP
Trailing \f[B]/\f[R] matches directories only.
No trailing \f[B]/\f[R] matches files only.
\f[B]\-\f[R] means don\[cq]t change that attribute.
Last matching rule wins.
.PP
If no \f[B]perms\f[R] file exists, all deployed files receive default
\f[B]0644\f[R] permissions and directories receive \f[B]0755\f[R] after
write.
Files are initially written with \f[B]0600\f[R] to prevent a window
where sensitive files are world\-readable, then lifted to the defaults
once the apply completes.
Add a \f[B]perms\f[R] file to override these defaults for specific
paths.
.SS Package and service management
Packages and services are managed via declarative \f[B]managers\f[R].
A manager defines command templates for \f[B]check\f[R],
\f[B]install\f[R], \f[B]remove\f[R], \f[B]enable\f[R], and
\f[B]disable\f[R].
Groups (e.g.\ \f[B][pacman]\f[R], \f[B][systemd]\f[R]) reference a
manager by name and list packages or services.
.IP
.EX
\f[B][managers.pacman]\f[R]
check   = \[dq]pacman \-Q {{.Name}}\[dq]
install = \[dq]sudo pacman \-S \-\-needed {{.Name}}\[dq]
remove  = \[dq]sudo pacman \-Rns {{.Name}}\[dq]

\f[B][managers.systemd]\f[R]
check   = \[dq]systemctl is\-enabled {{.Name}}\[dq]
enable  = \[dq]sudo systemctl enable {{.Name}}\[dq]
disable = \[dq]sudo systemctl disable {{.Name}}\[dq]

\f[B][pacman]\f[R]
packages = [\[dq]git\[dq], \[dq]neovim\[dq], \[dq]{{ if .laptop }}brightnessctl{{ end }}\[dq]]

\f[B][systemd]\f[R]
services = [\[dq]firewalld\[dq], \[dq]sshd\[dq]]
.EE
.PP
Package and service names may contain Go template expressions.
If a name renders to an empty string, the entry is skipped.
.PP
Template variables for commands: \- \f[B]{{.Name}}\f[R] \[em] raw
package/service name \- In check/install/remove/enable/disable:
\f[B]{{.Name}}\f[R] is shell\-quoted
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize a new dotfiles repo:
.IP
.EX
dotm init
.EE
.PP
Deploy files, symlinks, perms, and scripts:
.IP
.EX
dotm apply
.EE
.PP
Deploy everything including packages and services:
.IP
.EX
dotm apply \-\-all
.EE
.PP
Preview changes:
.IP
.EX
dotm apply \-n
.EE
.PP
Check current state of files:
.IP
.EX
dotm status
.EE
.PP
Check package status:
.IP
.EX
dotm status pkgs
.EE
.PP
Show all files including clean:
.IP
.EX
dotm status \-v
.EE
.PP
Show everything:
.IP
.EX
dotm status \-\-all
.EE
.PP
Diff against rendered source:
.IP
.EX
dotm diff
.EE
.PP
Show what packages would be installed/removed:
.IP
.EX
dotm diff pkgs
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Error.
Common causes: no command specified, config parse failure, template
error, permission apply failure, script execution failure.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.local/state/dotm/*.toml\f[R]
Per\-source\-repo state files (prompt answers, script hashes, manifest).
Filename is SHA\-256 hash of the source directory path.
